div.p:
To answer this I say M. Lilly did herein imitate

 the Ancients, who when as they were to deliver a publick Astrologicall judgement that would be bitter to the tast of most, did usually publish it in a dark sense, that none but the Sons of art might understand it; knowing that man could not endure to be toucht to the quick, and fearing lest they for sp aking such a truth plainly, should incurre the displeasure of most, and withall suffer an unjust punishment from great ones, who can hardly endure reproof: (this indeed I look on as the grand obstacle that men have laid in their own way to keep themselves from knowledge) so likewise as aforesaid hath Mr. Lilly without partiality, declared his judgement freely after an Astrologicall manner to those that understand it, that his said Majesty, Charles is the very man signified by this Comet: And very likely it was for the reasons before alleaged, that he did not declare this truth more plainely, knowing that it would be distastfull to the now greatest of this Nation, wherefore in the conclusion of his Astrologicall judgement of this Comets signification, sayes thus;
Video taceoque, sapit qui pauca scribit, plus, qui nihil.
